dth=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"330\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"170\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 170)\"></circle> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"448\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"448\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"506\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"66\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"406\" y1=\"66\" x2=\"406\" y2=\"166\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"407\" y1=\"65\" x2=\"508\" y2=\"168\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"302\" y1=\"65\" x2=\"400\" y2=\"65\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"330\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">1</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"470\" y=\"118\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">tan θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"60\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">cos θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"420\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\" dominant-baseline=\"central\" transform=\"rotate(90, 420, 128)\">sen θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"9\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">y</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"407\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"405\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">Q</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"500\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">R</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"520\" y=\"190\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">x</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 1</b>: Circle with radius 1 containing triangles and exposed trigonometric functions.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Our Position\n\n#### Introduction\n\nConsidering that the tangent, as explained previously, represents a point on the surface (<htcite0>), this leads us to an initial reflection:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "213a8932-84c2-4f72-9852-38368994d9a5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Do we tangent the planet?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: If and only if...</b><br /><br />As we have seen, the fact that we are tangent to the planet is an approximation; therefore, let's clarify this better.<br /><br />Look at yourself. In which position could you best represent a point touching the planet?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Growing Knowledge\n\nWe know, from previous texts, that the definition of the tangent (**Formula 1**) is given by the sine and cosine (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "213a8932-84c2-4f72-9852-38368994d9a5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Do we tangent the planet?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #FFFFFF;\"><p><math mathsize=\"1.5em\" displaystyle=\"false\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>tan (θ)</mi><mn>=</mn><mfrac><mi>sen(θ)</mi><mi>cos (θ)</mi></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Formula 1</b>: Definition of the tangent according to trigonometric functions.</p></div></div></center>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Furthermore, we have also studied the graphs of the sine and cosine functions in another text, in which we saw that, as the value of the cosine decreases, that of the sine increases (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1cc3be4f-110f-40eb-b281-d01378aae23f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Walking on the circle",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chartcossin2\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Graph of the sine and cosine functions and the trigonometric identity that unites them in the first quadrant of the circle. Graph created with the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotSineCosine('chartcossin2', true, true, 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Finally, we remember that we have also studied that it is not possible to divide by zero, but that, by means of limits, we can understand a value to be obtained from the quantities we are working with (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nWith this information, we can graph the tangent function.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3f68de7c-d729-4b62-9bb1-36c6f518fea4",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Simplicity vs. Complexity",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "09",
                        "day": "11"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Natural limits",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Understanding the Graph\n\nThe result of our tangent graph will be given by **Formula 1**, that is, it will be given by the division of the sine of theta (θ) by the cosine of theta (θ), with the value of the angle theta (θ) being equal for both trigonometric functions. Observing **Graph 2** which shows the values of sine and cosine for equal angles, we can conclude:\n- When the cosine has a value of zero, there will be no defined value. Therefore, this is a scenario in which we will use limits to understand towards which value the results approach as the cosine approaches zero; As seen in another text by *History Tracers*, between 0 and 1 there are infinite numbers (<htcite0>). Thus, when the value of the cosine of theta (θ) is equal to 1, then the value of the tangent will be equal to the value of the sine. For example, the value of the cosine is equal to 1 when the sine is equal to 0; therefore, the tangent will be equal to 0;\n- On the other hand, as the value of the cosine of theta decreases towards zero, the value of the tangent will increase; in this way, the value will tend towards infinity, not limiting itself to values between 0 and 1.\n\nTo better understand what we have described, see **Graph 3**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d06e24cb-52e8-4ff8-ae37-12052c91b187",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Limiting",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"charttan1\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 3</b>: Graph of the tangent function for the values shown in <b>Graph 1 and 2</b>. Graph created with the <htcite0> library.</div></p><script> htPlotTan('charttan1', 1);</script>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9",
                     "text": "Chart JS",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "05",
                        "day": "30"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### From one graph to another\n\nFrom **Graph 3**, we can also understand what happens to the tangent of theta (θ) in **Graph 1**. First, we will shift point **P** toward the **x** axis:",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p id=\"circtri2\"><style>.circle-draw circle, .circle-draw line {stroke: #71a6d2; stroke-width: 4; stroke-linecap: round; fill: none;} .circle-draw circle { stroke-dasharray: 942; stroke-dashoffset: 942; animation: drawCircle 2s linear forwards;} .radius-line { transform-origin: 300px 170px; animation: rotateRadius 2s linear forwards;} .radius-45 { opacity: 0; animation: showRadius45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .radius-30{ opacity: 0; animation: showRadius30 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .vertical45 { opacity: 0; animation: showVertical45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.5s; } .atlasTextRadius { opacity: 0; animation: atlasTextRadiusMov 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.8s; }</style><style>@keyframes drawCircle { to {stroke-dashoffset: 0; } } @keyframes rotateRadius { from { transform: rotate(0deg); } to   { transform: rotate(-360deg); } } @keyframes showRadius45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showRadius30 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showVertical45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes atlasTextRadiusMov { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }</style><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 340\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"520\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"8\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"330\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"170\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 170)\"></circle> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"448\" y2=\"169\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"448\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"506\" y2=\"169\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"360\" y=\"158\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">1</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"450\" y=\"190\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">tan θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"350\" y=\"185\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">cos θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"9\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">y</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"450\" y=\"168\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"425\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">Q</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"520\" y=\"190\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">x</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 4</b>: Circle with radius 1 containing triangles and some exposed trigonometric functions.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "By making the adjustment in **Graph 1**, generating **Graph 4**, we can observe that the sine is no longer visible when the angle theta (θ) reaches zero. We can also observe the absence of triangles, although our original hypotenuse and the cosine of theta (θ) are still shown with their expected maximum value, length 1.\n\nAn example for intermediate values is available in **Graph 1**, where both triangles are visible. In this graph, we would like to highlight a relevant point: although the hypotenuse is a straight line from the origin, the value of the tangent, as can be observed in **Graph 3**, is not linear.\n\nFinally, let's redraw **Graph 1** for some values close to the extreme shown in **Graph 2**.",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p id=\"circtri1\"><style>.circle-draw circle, .circle-draw line {stroke: #71a6d2; stroke-width: 4; stroke-linecap: round; fill: none;} .circle-draw circle { stroke-dasharray: 942; stroke-dashoffset: 942; animation: drawCircle 2s linear forwards;} .radius-line { transform-origin: 300px 170px; animation: rotateRadius 2s linear forwards;} .radius-45 { opacity: 0; animation: showRadius45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .radius-30{ opacity: 0; animation: showRadius30 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2s; } .vertical45 { opacity: 0; animation: showVertical45 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.5s; } .atlasTextRadius { opacity: 0; animation: atlasTextRadiusMov 0.3s ease-out forwards; animation-delay: 2.8s; }</style><style>@keyframes drawCircle { to {stroke-dashoffset: 0; } } @keyframes rotateRadius { from { transform: rotate(0deg); } to   { transform: rotate(-360deg); } } @keyframes showRadius45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showRadius30 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } } @keyframes showVertical45 { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }  @keyframes atlasTextRadiusMov { from { opacity: 0; } to { opacity: 1; } }</style><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 340\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"3\" markerHeight=\"3\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <path class=\"radius-30\" d=\"M 302 147 A 30 30 0 0 1 320.0 170.0\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"520\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"8\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"169\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"330\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" style=\"stroke: black;\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"170\" r=\"148\" transform=\"scale(-1 1) translate(-600 0)  rotate(180 300 170)\"></circle> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"300\" y1=\"169\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"22\"></line> <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"302\" y1=\"21\" x2=\"580\" y2=\"21\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"280\" y=\"88\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">1</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"320\" y=\"88\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\" dominant-baseline=\"central\" transform=\"rotate(90, 320, 88)\">sen θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"302\" y=\"165\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"187\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"282\" y=\"9\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">y</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"307\" y=\"17\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"520\" y=\"190\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">x</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 5</b>: Circle with radius 1 containing triangles and some exposed trigonometric functions.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Graph 5** shows us that there is no defined cosine of theta (θ) when the hypotenuse is completely vertical. Furthermore, as we had already mentioned, there is no definition for the tangent of theta (θ), which is not shown in this graph; however, we show its trajectory tending to infinity on the **x** axis (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Natural limits",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: Go off on a tangent</b><br /><br />When looking at the graphs in this text, do they help you understand what the expression “go off on a tangent” means?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Pointing vertically\n\nReturning to our initial reflection, with the knowledge acquired in this text and the previous one (<htcite0>), we can conclude that we are closer to tangenting the planet when we are standing, because, in this case, we reduce our contact area with the planet, approaching a point.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "213a8932-84c2-4f72-9852-38368994d9a5",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
